_help_export() {
    cat << 'EOF'
dotfiles export: export the local layer to the private repo

Copies your user-owned local files (local.conf overrides, ~/.zshrc, personal
launchers, copy-on-install configs) into the configured private repo and
commits. Secrets are never exported.

Pass one or more selectors to export only those entries; a partial export
scopes the commit to just what it captured. A selector matches a manifest
entry by its repo-relative path, path suffix, basename, or system path, or a
single file inside the launchers dir (e.g. launchers/acme).

USAGE
  dotfiles export [OPTIONS] [SELECTOR...]

OPTIONS
  -p, --push     Push to origin after committing
  -h, --help     Show this help

EXAMPLES
  dotfiles export                     # Capture everything and commit locally
  dotfiles export --push              # Capture all, commit, and push
  dotfiles export zshrc               # Capture just ~/.zshrc
  dotfiles export tmux/local.conf     # Capture one override by path suffix
  dotfiles export launchers/acme      # Capture a single launcher
EOF
}

_help_health() {
    cat << 'EOF'
dotfiles health — run a full installation health check

USAGE
  dotfiles health [OPTIONS]

OPTIONS
  -h, --help     Show this help

EXAMPLES
  dotfiles health
EOF
}

_help_import() {
    cat << 'EOF'
dotfiles import: import the local layer from the private repo

Pulls the configured private repo (when a remote is set) and applies its
files to this machine. Existing files that differ are left alone unless
--force is given; launcher files the repo no longer tracks are reported as
orphans and only deleted under --prune, so machine-local launchers survive a
--force. Symlinked destinations are never touched.

Pass one or more selectors to import only those entries. A selector matches a
manifest entry by its repo-relative path, path suffix, basename, or system
path, or a single file inside the launchers dir (e.g. launchers/acme).

USAGE
  dotfiles import [OPTIONS] [SELECTOR...]

OPTIONS
  -f, --force    Overwrite differing system files (never deletes orphans)
  -p, --prune    Delete launchers not tracked in the repo
  -h, --help     Show this help

EXAMPLES
  dotfiles import                    # Apply everything, skipping files that differ
  dotfiles import --force            # Overwrite differing files, keep orphans
  dotfiles import --force --prune    # Overwrite and prune orphaned launchers
  dotfiles import zshrc --force      # Pull just ~/.zshrc, overwriting it
  dotfiles import launchers/acme     # Pull a single launcher
EOF
}

_help_links() {
    cat << 'EOF'
dotfiles links — show all managed symlinks and their status

USAGE
  dotfiles links [OPTIONS]
  dotfiles -l

OPTIONS
  -h, --help     Show this help

EXAMPLES
  dotfiles links
EOF
}

_help_local() {
    cat << 'EOF'
dotfiles local: manage the private local-layer repo

The local layer (local.* overrides, ~/.zshrc, personal launchers,
copy-on-install configs) can be synced across your own machines via a
private git repo. The repo is referenced only by a machine-local pointer
(~/.config/dotfiles/local-repo, or the DOTFILES_LOCAL_DIR env var); the
public dotfiles repo never knows about it. Secrets are never synced.

USAGE
  dotfiles local [SUBCOMMAND] [ARGS]

SUBCOMMANDS
  status               Show configured repo, sync state (default)
  init [url]           Create a repo (default: ~/.dotfiles-local), register it
  clone <url>          Clone an existing private repo, register and apply it
  diff                 Show system vs repo differences
  edit                 Open the local-layer repo in $EDITOR

URLs accept GitHub "owner/repo" shorthand, expanded to https://github.com/.

OPTIONS
  --dir <path>   Use a custom repo location (init, clone)
  -h, --help     Show this help

EXAMPLES
  dotfiles local init you/dotfiles-local
  dotfiles export --push       # capture this machine, push

  dotfiles local clone you/dotfiles-local
                               # on another machine: registers + applies
  dotfiles import              # pick up later changes on demand
EOF
}

